# AI Agent Instructions

## Communication Style
- Be concise and direct
- Minimal preamble or postamble
- Save details for unfinished tasks or next steps, not accomplishments
- Answer exactly what's asked, nothing more

## Documentation Rules
- Keep dev logs high-level (what we worked on, not how)
- Track open conversations, unfinished work, and blockers
- All details go in docs/context.txt, not in dev logs
- Update docs/devlogs/v*.txt daily with brief entries
- Always update today's devlog entry before committing to git
- Update devlog in the same commit that contains the changes being documented

## File Management
- NEVER create files unless absolutely necessary
- ALWAYS prefer editing existing files over creating new ones
- NEVER proactively create documentation or README files unless explicitly requested

## Questions
- Ask maximum 2 questions at a time
- Track open conversations in docs/context.txt so nothing is forgotten

## Project Structure
- Dev logs: docs/devlogs/v1.txt (will split by version if needed)
- Context file: docs/context.txt (current project status, open items, project-specific info - NOT AI behavior rules)
- Requirements: docs/requirements.md (tree structure: features → use cases with checkboxes)

## File Updates & Confirmations
- When user requests new AI behaviors/workflows → proactively detect and propose adding to .aidescription, ask confirmation first
- When adding to docs/context.txt → ask confirmation first on what will be added
- Detect when user describes new rules/behaviors and offer to document them

## File Formats & Examples

### docs/requirements.md
Tree structure: features → use cases with checkboxes
- Finalized feature decisions with checkboxes
- Draft/undecided features marked with [DRAFT] prefix
- [DRAFT] items also remain in docs/context.txt "Open Conversations"

Example:
## Version 1

### Feature: User Authentication
- [ ] User can sign up with email
- [ ] User can log in
  - [ ] Remember me option
- [ ] User can reset password

### Feature: [DRAFT] Social Login
- [ ] Login with Google
- [ ] Login with Facebook

### docs/devlogs/v*.txt
Daily entries, high-level accomplishments only
Example:
## 2026-01-06

### What We Accomplished
- Set up project structure

### What's Unfinished
- Define app requirements
- Build authentication flow

### docs/context.txt
Sections: Open Conversations, Restrictions, Requirements, Bugs
- Open/undecided decisions and discussions
- [DRAFT] requirements from requirements.md
- Current project status and next steps
Keep concise, track current project state only

## Code Standards

### Naming Conventions
- Variables/functions: camelCase
- Components/classes: PascalCase
- Event handlers: use `on` prefix (e.g., onClick, onSubmit)

### File Organization
- One component per file
- Component filename matches component name (PascalCase)
- Type/interface location TBD (will discuss structure later)

### Code Quality
- No duplicated code - extract into reusable functions/components
- Apply TDD (Test-Driven Development)
- Refactor before committing
- Don't patch bugs - debug root cause and fix properly
- Clean, maintainable code over quick fixes

### Documentation & Explanations
- Explain what code does before committing
- Maintain architecture diagrams (UML or similar) showing how components/classes interact
- Maintain entity relationship diagram for database structure
- Maintain JSON Schema (docs/database-schema.json) for database validation
- Keep diagrams in docs/architecture/ folder
- Update diagrams and schema when adding/changing major components or entities

## Git Workflow

### Commit Message Format
Format: `type(scope): description`
- Type: `feat` or `fix`
- Scope: generic feature name in parentheses
- Description: complete the phrase "If applied, this commit will..."
  - Keep it short and imperative mood
  - Example: `feat(auth): add user login functionality`
  - Example: `fix(api): handle empty response errors`
- NEVER add "Generated with Claude Code" or "Co-Authored-By" footers
- Keep commit messages concise

